<div id="review_3601217429" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3601217429" />
    <a title="Olivier Delaye" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9854601-olivier-delaye"><img alt="Olivier Delaye" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582470792p2/9854601.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3601217429?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Olivier Delaye" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Olivier Delaye" href="/user/show/9854601-olivier-delaye">Olivier Delaye</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3601217429" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2903172105594045510">What took me so long to dive into this little wonder of a book? And what a delight it was when I finally did! Sure, it’s a children’s tale, but there’s, I think, a little bit of everything for everyone in these pages: adventure and discovery, sorrow and joy, allegory and symbolism (for those willing to find them), and above all a pitch-perfect choice of words which is often oh-so tricky to master when writing primarily for children. If I had to pick only one word to describe this book, it would </span>
  <span id="freeText2903172105594045510" style="display:none">What took me so long to dive into this little wonder of a book? And what a delight it was when I finally did! Sure, it’s a children’s tale, but there’s, I think, a little bit of everything for everyone in these pages: adventure and discovery, sorrow and joy, allegory and symbolism (for those willing to find them), and above all a pitch-perfect choice of words which is often oh-so tricky to master when writing primarily for children. If I had to pick only one word to describe this book, it would be cute. But cute in the purest sense of the word without any sarcastic or condescending undertone. Cute as in attractive in a graceful way, in a dainty way, without ever being mawkish or cheesy… which in itself is quite a feat as, after all, we're dealing with talking mice and rats here. Sorry, couldn’t help myself.<br><br>OLIVIER DELAYE<br>Author of the SEBASTEN OF ATLANTIS series<br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/32848933.The_Forgotten_Goddess__Sebasten_of_Atlantis___1_" title="The Forgotten Goddess (Sebasten of Atlantis, #1) by Olivier Delaye" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1477999967l/32848933._SY75_.jpg" alt="The Forgotten Goddess (Sebasten of Atlantis, #1) by Olivier Delaye" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="2903172105594045510" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

